<h2>Method 2: Copy Text Directly in Your PDF Reader</h2>

<p>
  For text-based PDFs, the simplest method is just selecting and copying:
</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>In Chrome/Edge (any OS):</strong> Open PDF → click and drag to select text → Ctrl+C (or Cmd+C on Mac).</li>
  <li><strong>In Adobe Acrobat Reader:</strong> Click the cursor tool → select text → right-click → Copy. Or Edit → Copy to get all text on a page.</li>
  <li><strong>Select all text:</strong> Ctrl+A (or Cmd+A) while viewing a PDF in a browser selects all text on the current page.</li>
</ul>
<p>
  If the text is not selectable, the PDF is either a scanned image or has copy restrictions enabled. See the methods below for those cases.
</p>

<h2>Method 3: Extract Text From a Scanned PDF Using Google Docs (Free OCR)</h2>

<p>
  Google Docs automatically applies OCR when you open a PDF — this works even on scanned documents:
</p>
<ol>
  <li>Go to <strong>Google Drive</strong> (drive.google.com).</li>
  <li>Upload the scanned PDF.</li>
  <li>Right-click the PDF → <strong>Open with → Google Docs</strong>.</li>
  <li>Google applies OCR and opens the document with recognised text.</li>
  <li>Select all (Ctrl+A) and copy, or work with it directly in Google Docs.</li>
  <li>Download as Word or plain text via File → Download.</li>
</ol>
<p>
  Quality of OCR depends on the scan quality. Good scans of printed text produce excellent results; handwritten text or very low-resolution scans may have errors.
</p>

<h2>Method 4: Extract Text on Mac with Preview</h2>

<ol>
  <li>Open the PDF in <strong>Preview</strong>.</li>
  <li>Go to <strong>Edit → Select All</strong> (Cmd+A) to select all text on the page.</li>
  <li>Copy with Cmd+C.</li>
</ol>
<p>
  Alternatively, go to <strong>File → Export → Text</strong> in some versions of Preview to save the text content as a .txt file.
</p>

<h2>Method 5: Use Python to Extract PDF Text (for Developers)</h2>

<p>
  If you need to extract text from many PDFs programmatically, Python makes it easy:
</p>

<pre><code>pip install pypdf2

from PyPDF2 import PdfReader

reader = PdfReader("document.pdf")
text = ""
for page in reader.pages:
    text += page.extract_text()

print(text)</code></pre>

<p>
  For scanned PDFs, combine with <code>pytesseract</code> for OCR:
</p>

<pre><code>pip install pytesseract pdf2image pillow

from pdf2image import convert_from_path
import pytesseract

pages = convert_from_path("scanned.pdf")
text = ""
for page in pages:
    text += pytesseract.image_to_string(page)

print(text)</code></pre>

<h2>Why Text Extraction Fails (And How to Fix It)</h2>

<h3>The PDF is a scanned image</h3>
<p>
  Scanned PDFs contain images of pages — there is no text layer. Solution: use Google Docs OCR (Method 3 above) or a dedicated OCR tool.
</p>

<h3>Text copying is restricted</h3>
<p>
  The PDF owner may have set a permission that prevents copying. Solution: if you know the PDF password, open it with the password in Chrome and use Ctrl+P → Save as PDF to create an unrestricted copy.
</p>

<h3>Non-standard encoding or fonts</h3>
<p>
  Some PDFs with unusual embedded fonts extract as garbled characters. This is a PDF structure issue — a different PDF-to-text tool or OCR is the usual workaround.
</p>

<h3>Right-to-left or complex scripts</h3>
<p>
  Arabic, Hebrew, and some Asian scripts may extract with character order issues in some tools. Adobe Acrobat handles these better than browser-based tools.
</p>

<h2>When to Use PDF to Text vs PDF to Word</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Use PDF to Text when:</strong> you only need the raw text content without formatting — for feeding into another tool, copying a quote, or analysing content.</li>
  <li><strong>Use PDF to Word when:</strong> you need to edit the document while preserving the original formatting, headings, tables, and images. Note that PDF to Word conversion is never perfect for complex layouts.</li>
</ul>

